<paragraph id="E8403669FF80FFFCFE2D19B18624B1DC" blockId="23.[436,880,956,983]" box="[436,880,956,983]" pageId="23" pageNumber="822">
<heading id="B3088105FF80FFFCFE2D19B18624B1DC" box="[436,880,956,983]" centered="true" fontSize="11" level="2" pageId="23" pageNumber="822" reason="5">
<taxonomicName id="2FFF4DEAFF80FFFCFE2D19B18624B1DC" authority="(Muttkowski, 1910)" baseAuthorityName="Muttkowski" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[436,880,956,983]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Tramea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="23" pageNumber="822" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="calverti">
<emphasis id="DA8BEA7BFF80FFFCFE2D19B18729B1DC" bold="true" box="[436,637,956,983]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="822">Tramea calverti</emphasis>
(Muttkowski, 1910)
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E8403669FF80FFFCFF5919FF84ECB6F6" blockId="23.[160,1156,1010,1277]" pageId="23" pageNumber="822">
Adults are large, red, with the hindwing bearing a longitudinal brown-red basal spot, and the thorax is red to brown with two oblique, white bars on each side. 
<taxonomicName id="2FFF4DEAFF80FFFCFC451E1981D7B626" baseAuthorityName="Muttkowski" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[988,1155,1044,1069]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Tramea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="23" pageNumber="822" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="calverti">
<emphasis id="DA8BEA7BFF80FFFCFC451E1981D7B626" box="[988,1155,1044,1069]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="822">Tramea calverti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was almost as widespread in our surveys across St. Thomas as was 
<taxonomicName id="2FFF4DEAFF80FFFCFC131E3A817DB65B" baseAuthorityName="Rambur" baseAuthorityYear="1842" box="[906,1065,1079,1104]" class="Insecta" family="Libellulidae" genus="Tramea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="23" pageNumber="822" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="abdominalis">
<emphasis id="DA8BEA7BFF80FFFCFC131E3A817DB65B" box="[906,1065,1079,1104]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="822">T. abdominalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but we never found it where there was brackish water or mangrove forests. It was not reported by 
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF80FFFCFF391E718400B69E" author="Donnelly N" box="[160,340,1148,1173]" pageId="23" pageNumber="822" pagination="7 - 9" refId="ref24517" refString="Donnelly N. 2002. Odonata of St. Thomas and St. John, Virgin Islands. Argia. 14 (1): 7 - 9." type="journal article" year="2002">Donnelly (2002)</bibRefCitation>
, but 
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF80FFFCFE091E718776B69E" author="Sibley F" box="[400,546,1148,1173]" pageId="23" pageNumber="822" pagination="16 - 19" refId="ref30069" refString="Sibley F. 1999. Unusual invasion of dragonflies on Guana Islands, British Virgin Islands, 1999. Argia. 11 (1): 16 - 19." type="journal article" year="1999">Sibley (1999)</bibRefCitation>
reported this species colonising Guana and 
<collectingCountry id="90E876F9FF80FFFCFB861E7181D7B69E" box="[1055,1155,1148,1173]" name="British Virgin Islands" pageId="23" pageNumber="822">Anegada</collectingCountry>
islands and speculated that it could have jumped to other 
<collectingCountry id="90E876F9FF80FFFCFCAB1E928140B6B3" box="[818,1044,1183,1208]" name="British Virgin Islands" pageId="23" pageNumber="822">British Virgin Islands</collectingCountry>
as well. It was found at two sites in 
<collectingCountry id="90E876F9FF80FFFCFE211ECF8763B6D0" box="[440,567,1218,1243]" name="Puerto Rico" pageId="23" pageNumber="822">Puerto Rico</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="8C6E4B98FF80FFFCFDDA1ECF8641B6D0" author="Ramirez A &amp; Maldonado-Benitez N &amp; Mariani-Rios A &amp; Figueroa-Santiago J" box="[579,789,1218,1243]" pageId="23" pageNumber="822" pagination="9711" refId="ref28863" refString="Ramirez A, Maldonado-Benitez N, Mariani-Rios A, Figueroa-Santiago J. 2020. Dragonflies and damselflies (Odonata) from Puerto Rico: a checklist with notes on distribution and habitat. PeerJ. 8: e 9711. doi: 10.7717 / peerj. 9711." type="journal article" year="2020">Ram√≠rez et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
), but this is the first record of the species from St. Thomas.
</paragraph>
